text: Alright, everyone who hates the movies compares its bad points with the book. Let's have a peek at the book then, SHALL WE? The bad points of the book: 1) During the dwarven gathering in his house, Bilbo remains despicably polite. And an answer to an "At your service" as "thank you" instead of "At yours" is considered rude. That's an EXAGGERATION. 2) Dwalin's beard is blue. REALLY? 3) The Elven King of Mirkwood's name is probably the Elven King of Mirkwood, because that's what everyone calls him. PJ giving him the name from LOTR and a personality of his own, and  amotivation to go to Erebor that's not riches, was a crime of the Director's side, right? PF. 4) Half of Middle-Earth knows that Bilbo has a magic ring. Like what a surprise it would be later to see that it'sSauron's ring. 5) Gollum is more described as a marine fish creature. 6) If the movies were made exactly like the book, then half of them would be songs. Songs, songs and again SONGS! 7) I can't imagine the elves of Rivendell dancing and singing "Tralala" and "Hahaha" all the time. 8) Bard appears out of nowhere as a descendant of Girion, kills the dragon and instantly becomes King. At least in the movies he was given a proper background, a clearer picture of his family and a better reason as to why people liked him. 9) In the movies, Bilbo hid the Arkenstone for fear of corrupting Thorin. In the book, the only first reason he did so was because of the dragon's words made him think that the dwarves would not give him the right fourteenth he deserved, so he took what was most valuable in there. Yes, Bilbo's main motivation in getting the Arkenstone was self-interest. Doesn't matter that he wanted to prevent wars laters, by giving it away. 10) Tolkien gave a better background for Thror, and a better reason why Smaug attacked Erebor anyway. Plus, he in a magnificent way supports the possibility that we have for having read the "Silmarillion", that the Arkenstone might be a Silmarillion and a reason of corruption. After all, one of them was lost beneath tons of rock, right? In the book, it's just a cool stone. And a reason for the others to be sort of persuasive to Thorin. 11) Elrond didn't know what Durin's day is. Yeah, sure. 12) The trolls captured the dwarves one by one, and people protest  of why they didn't do so in the movie, but there was an unneded fight. Well, I myself prefered 2 minutes of action, rather than 4 minutes of dwarves coming one after another in the troll camp like idiots and getting captured, only with Thorin giving resistance. 13) The fact that we're shown of the Necromancer and his escapades for Dol Guldur in the movie is awesome. And why not? Did you guys want it to be an extra movie? OR th book Gandalf, leaving his friends behind in the msot dangerous part of their road trip, for "some business"? 14) Legolas doesn't exist. Of course, Tolkien hadn't thought of him yet, but he was at least 2000 years old by then. Does that give him a reason not to appear as th PRince of Mirkwood or not? For Pete's sake, all this hate for changes TOLKIEN HIMSELF WANTED TO DO TO CONNECT WITH LOTR> But because PJ did them, he's a villain. 15) Most of dwarves only appear in one line or as names. an you tell different Bifur, Bofur, Ori, Nori? No. Oin and GLoin where also just fire-lighters, nothing else for the team. At least the movies gave them their own personalities and backkground for each of them. 16) THe only reason THorin made peace with Bilbo before he died, was because it was a pity to be at war with the hobbit even after death. Not completely because he suddenly changed his mind. At least in the movies we see his corruption from the Arkenstone ANDhow he fought it, on the contrary with THror, and changed mind, so he end befriended with Bilbo again. 17) Suddenly a Bolg son of Azog appears out of nowhere with 1/3 of Gundabaad Goblins.  18) Bolg died with one strike. Yeah, that was so much of suspense. 19) There was no Azog. So what? You're afraid thatDain woul lose his title as Ironfoot? 20) At least the dwarves gave a try to kill the dragon, they did'n hide like cowards from the book or they didn't send Bilbo in 3 times just to check if thr dragon is still there.. Like WTF  Now I get why Tolkien wanted to change the book. But he died, unfortunately, and now every hater of the movie claims the book as canon. GG easy. Well done.  At last, to mention the all-time hated romance of Kili and Tauriel in the movie. Only negative of it was, it would end in so much a tragedy for Kili dies.  Like, stop hating like Orcs already. AN extra pinch of suspense never hurt anyway, it's a Hollywood movie after all. Overall, what did we see in the movies: 13 Dwarves and a hobbit embark from hobbiton, reach rivendell, get captured by goblins, a gollum loses a ring which goes to Bilbo, they meet the Eagles, then Beorn, get lost in Mirkwood and captured by spiders and Elves, reach Erebor, the dragon dies by BARD, there's a five army battle won thanks to the Eagles, and Thorin-Fili-Kili die, with Bilbo returning home. IF THOSE WERE BOTH IN THER BOOK AND IN THE MOVIE, WAS IT NECESSARY TO CRY ABOUT THE MOVIE EXTRAS, ALL BASED ON TOLKIEN WORK, AND GIVING US EXTRA TIME IN MIDDLE EARTH? JESUS! Thanks Mister JAckson for the magnificent work, on my opinion, and may you soon return.

text: People can diss this trilogy as many times as they want. I still absolutelly love it. And I am perfectly aware that TLOTR trilogy is better. But this one has something in addition. Although the script is very loose since it was dilute in three movies, Peter Jackson made use of his incredible directing talent to get it together. And instead of crying about it, I totally enjoyed it. So, yes, not much happens, but what happens gets me with the eyes on the screen, because PJ put extra effort in the details, craft work, the camera work, the armors, lighting, texture, composition, cinematography, music, etc And yes, the story lacks sinthesis but the production design, graphic art and music were enhanced the double to cover those flaws, and the cinematographic language had to be refined even more to have more coherence, so I thank for that because it mad it some of the most gorgeous movies I have ever watched.

text: While I do love that song from Return of the King, I think it’s use its use here really drives home how the Hobbit films were constantly relying on the audiences nostalgia for a trilogy of far better films.  Despite being canon to one another, the Hobbit as a book doesn’t feel like LotR and the films tried way too hard to make the Hobbit work as a much more direct prequel both narratively and tonally while throwing characters and imagery at you often for no other reason than to say “remember Lord of the Rings? Weren’t those movies good? This is the same universe so these movies are good too.”  I just wish the studio would’ve let LotR stand on its own and gone ahead and let the Hobbit be it’s own lighthearted quirky thing. Still canon, but unique in tone and style. But I understand the choice and the films aren’t terrible, just not as good as they could’ve been.

text: "Those who survived... and those who did not..." It doesn't matter that I know how this movie ends. I still need a surgery to remove my goosebumps! The two trilogies are beautieful! A truly masterpiece. It is impossible to make a movie 1:1 to the book. A movie is for entertainment, a book for meditation, because the process of absorbing information by reading is different to the process of viewing. So it was good that the movie was modified to the modern media, without twisting the whole storyline. Peter Jackson did a damn good job. Ian Mckellen brought the original book in the set. That's what I like. A director and the producers who are able to work with the actors and the crew as equal. A very efficiant and creative way to make it possible to bring a work on screen that seems too impossible to be shown in a medium like cinema.
